ected based on sky and atmospheric conditions. For each of the five\nDES-SN seasons, a separate coadd is made from the other 4 seasons such that\neach SN has a corresponding deep coadd with no contaminating SN emission. The\ncoadds reach limiting magnitudes of order $\\sim 27$ in $g$-band, and have a\nmuch smaller magnitude uncertainty than the previous DES-SN host templates,\nparticularly for faint objects. We present the resulting multi-band photometry\nof host galaxies for samples of spectroscopically confirmed type Ia (SNe Ia),\ncore-collapse (CCSNe), and superluminous (SLSNe) as well as rapidly evolving\ntransients (RETs) discovered by DES-SN. We derive host galaxy stellar masses\nand probabilistically compare stellar-mass distributions to samples from other\nsurveys. We find that the DES spectroscopically confirmed sample of SNe Ia\nselects preferentially fewer high mass hosts at high redshift compared to other\nsurveys, while at low redshift the distributions are consistent. DES CCSNe and\nSLSNe hosts are similar to other samples, while RET hosts are unlike the hosts\nof any other transients, although these differences have not been disentangled\nfrom selection effects.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 8 Jan 2020 17:22:46 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-05-27"}
